    "narrative": "The strongest play on the board for LawDog today is **Geraldo Perdomo**, who leads the lineup with a 68.41 score. Batting leadoff against a vulnerable arm in Martin (4.68 xERA), **Geraldo Perdomo** benefits from a massive 17% SP skill adjustment and a 10% premium for the leadoff spot, making him the anchor for our production. **Bryson Stott** (62.02) also presents a strong start; his matchup against Cabrera is mitigated by a helpful wind-out factor and a significant 13% platoon boost, which effectively counters the concern of facing a competent arm. Meanwhile, **Matt Chapman** (57.18) remains a high-floor play despite the tough task of facing Glasnow. The algorithm notes that Glasnow\u2019s slow delivery offers a rare opportunity for **Matt Chapman** to leverage his speed, providing a small but necessary boost to his offensive outlook in our scarce SB environment.\n\nThe bench decisions were largely dictated by the schedule, as **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez**, **Cal Raleigh**, **Lawrence Butler**, and **Will Smith** are all unavailable due to off-days or rest. Among those who could have started, **Drew Gilbert** (43.24) and **Wenceel Perez** (45.20) occupy the bottom tier of our lineup. **Wenceel Perez** was nearly relegated to the bench in favor of roster depth, but his moderate projection survives due to the favorable matchup against Sproat. **Drew Gilbert** serves as the most fragile start of the day; while he gains marginal utility from the slow delivery of Glasnow, his #8 spot in the order severely caps his run-producing potential. We are proceeding with caution, as Glasnow represents an elite-tier hurdle that drags down the efficiency scores for **Luis Arraez**, **Jung Hoo Lee**, and **Drew Gilbert** across the board.",
